\subsubsection{Source description}
We show the moment maps of HCG~16 in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg16_mom}. SoFiA detected 10 \HI\ sources. Their properties will be discussed further in a subsequent paper. 
The moment one map in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg16_mom} is plotted in a way that each individual sources are scaled by different color-scaling factor to highlight any rotational 
patterns. While the surrounding sources show differential rotation, the core members do not, and their iso-velocity contours are disturbed.  
The most remarkable finding here is the presence of numerous tidal features and clumps, as well as a long, continuous tidal tail connecting the core member of the group and NGC 848. 
In addition, a hook-like structure extends south-east of NGC 848 before curving to the north west in direction parallel to the main group. To better visualize the tails, 
we show segmented position-velocity diagrams in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg16_pvd} as previously done by \citet{2019A&A...632A..78J} using VLA data. 
The pv-diagrams are taken from the paths shown in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg16_pvd_path}. Most of the tails were previously identified 
by the VLA map of \citet{2019A&A...632A..78J} and we adopt the author's nomenclature to name them. However, the tails are more pronounced in the MeerKAT map. 
Note also that the curved tail (hook) was not visible in the VLA map. As shown in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg16_pvd_path}, all core members are linked by tails or high column density bridge. 
There is a continuity in velocity between NGC 848S and the curved tail. The hook appears to be a stretched gas from NGC 848 due to its encounter with the main group. 
The presence of numerous tails and clumps are typical of compact groups at the intermediate stage, indicating substantial gas loss into the IGM.   
