\subsection{HCG 30}
\subsubsection{Data cube}
The data cube of HCG~30 has a synthesized beam size of \SI{60.47}{\arcsecond} $\times$ \SI{59.77}{\arcsecond}, with a 3$\sigma$ column density sensitivity limit of \qty{6.1e+18}{cm^{-2}} 
over \qty{20}{km~s^{-1}}. The noise is well-behaved, without any apparent signs of continuum residuals or cleaning artefacts. The global profile is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg30_noise}. 
The recovered flux from MeerKAT is \qty{40.05}{Jy~km~s^{-1}}, giving a total mass of \qty{3.51e+10}{} $M_{\odot}$. The recovered flux from the VLA is \qty{15.14}{Jy~km~s^{-1}}, 
corresponding to a total mass of \qty{1.3e+10}{} $M_{\odot}$. 
\subsubsection{Source description}
HCG~30 is one of the most \HI\ deficient groups in our sample and previous observations failed to detect any \HI\ emission in the galaxies making up its core. However, 
we detect \HI\ emission at the location of HCG~30b and HCG~30c. The \HI\ emission corresponding to HCG~30b was splitted as three sources by SoFiA. We combined the three 
individual cubelettes from SoFiA using the MIRIAD task \texttt{IMCOMB} and rederived the moment maps, which we show in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg30b}. These plots were generated 
using the SoFiA Image Pipeline (SIP) by Hess K.M. (\href{https://github.com/kmhess/SoFiA-image-pipeline}{https://github.com/kmhess/SoFiA-image-pipeline}). The moment one 
map presents apparent signs of rotation but the iso-velocity contours do not show the spider patterns expected from Sa galaxies. Instead, they show systematically convex 
curvatures. Note though that the emission along the minor axis is barely resolved. The global \HI\ profile exhibits an enhanced intensity at either side of a more subdued 
central peak. However, the overall S/N of the profile is low.  We detect \HI\ emission corresponding 
to the location of HCG~31c. The systemic velocity we got from SIP, \qty{4519}{km~s^{-1}}, corresponds well to the one quoted by \citet{2023A&A...670A..21J}, \qty{4508}{km~s^{-1}}, 
from its optical redshift. However, the emission is faint and is barely resolved. We show the overview plots of HCG~30c from SIP in \ref{fig:hcg30c}. Disk rotation is not detected due 
to insufficient S/N ratio and resolution elements. The \HI\ detection in HCG~30a remains spurious and unresolved despite being a large spiral galaxy.   
\\\\
We present the example channel maps of HCG~30 in Figure~\ref{fig:hcg30_chanmap}. These only show the channels corresponding to the receding side of HCG~30b, the rest is presented 
as online-only material. Overall, the emission is faint and is mostly below the 3$\sigma$ detection threshold.   
